Subject : *Seeking co-operation as a son of Mukthijoddah to continue job in Rohingya camp based United Nations (UNHCR and IOM ) funded INGO/ NGO*

Dear Sir:::

With due respect:::I would like to inform you that I am a son of Mukthijoddah name Abdul Hakim from Chattogram. My father demised on the 13th of May:::2020. On the 15th of May 2020::: I got forced end of contact letter because of Covid-19 break out. I had been working in *UNHCR and IOM funded Child Protection* *Project* of *Terre des hommes(Tdh) an INGO as Child Protection MHPSS (Mental Health Psychosocial Social Support ) Officer* from the 15th of October 2018 till the 30 th of June 2020.My father took 3 lac taka bank loan against freedom fighters monthly honourium. Because of the bank installment payment::: my father would get 10000 taka monthly as freedom fighters honourium. My mother::: my university going sister and my family is totally dependant on my earnings. Moreover::: my family lives in a rented house. Now I got tumour on my neck and I could not take treatment because of fimancial crisis. It is quite difficult to get a new job because of Covid-19 pendemic.I shall be grateful to you if you recommend for me to be reinstated in my job in *Terre des hommes or any other INGO/ NGO as a Child Protection MH PSS( Mental Health Psychosocial Support) Officer or any other suitable post*. I prefer to work in *INGO* ( International NGO) because they pay high salary by which I can maintain the expenses for my large family. In Terre des hommes (Tdh) I used to get taka 55:::150 equal to US dollars 687 monthly salary.

Best regards:::
Mohammad Abdur Rahman
Chittagong.
Bangladesh

*Rohingyas have found refuge in Bangladesh* *as the freedom fighters have liberated Bangladesh. As Rohingyas have taken refuge in Bangladesh::: Rohingya camp-centric NGOs are getting millions and millions of foreign aid to run their activities. So::: can't the children of freedom fighters get priority in employment in Rohingya camp-centric NGOs* ?I have been applying for jobs in Rohingya camp-centric NGOs for one year but have not yet receive a phone call for an interview.

column4:
When I was a student at MIT (undergrad and grad)::: I was often the only female in a class (of any subject!). No one ever cared whether I was ‚Äúcomfortable‚Äù and that was not a priority for me. I was at MIT to work hard and there was no time or energy to worry about being ‚Äúcomfortable‚Äù. I earned three degrees in EE (all before my 22nd birthday) and then worked about 40 years in a profession in which I was never ‚Äúcomfortable‚Äù. In my work::: I suffered discrimination:::
humiliation::: public physical assault::: propositions::: you name it. But I always worked hard and did the best that I could. I was able to support myself and acquire retirement income.

The honor commemorates Danny Lewin SM ‚Äô98::: who was one of nearly 3:::000 people who died in the terrorist attacks of September 11::: 2001. Lewin was killed onboard American Airlines Flight 11::: and is credited with trying to stop the plane from crashing into the World Trade Center. Although his life was cut short at 31::: Lewin made an indelible mark on the field of computer science. He was co-founder of Akamai Technologies and a doctoral candidate at MIT at the time of his death.

... Most of the tests that doctors use to cancer diagnose ‚Äî such as mammography::: colonoscopy::: and CT scans ‚Äî are based on imaging. More recently::: researchers have also developed molecular diagnostics that can detect specific cancer-associat
ed molecules that circulate in bodily fluids like blood or urine. MIT engineers have now created a new diagnostic nanoparticle that combines both of these features: It can reveal the presence of cancerous proteins through a urine test ::: and it functions as an imaging agent::: pinpointing the tumor location. In principle::: this diagnostic could be used to detect cancer anywhere in the body::: including tumors that have metastasized from their original locations. to both primary tumors and their metastases. It can trigger a urinary signal and also allow us to visualize where the tumors are:::‚Äù says Sangeeta Bhatia::: the John and Dorothy Wilson Professor of Health Sciences and Technology and Elec trical Engineering and Computer Science at MIT and a member of MIT's Koch Institute for Integrative Cancer Research and Institute for Medical Engineering and Science.In a new study::: Bhatia and her colleagues showed that the diagnostic could be used to monitor the progression of colon cancer::: including the spread of metastatic tumors to the lung and the liver. Eventually::: they hope it could be developed into a routine cancer test that could be performed annually.Bhatia
is the senior author of the study::: which appears today in Nature Materials. The paper's lead author is MIT research scientist Liangliang Hao. Over the past several years::: Bhatia has been developing cancer diagnostics that work by generating synthetic biomarkers that can be easily detected in the urine. Most cancer cells express enzymes called proteases::: which help them escape their original locations by cutting through proteins of the extracellular matrix. Bhatia's cancer-detectin
g nanoparticles are coated with peptides that are cleaved by these proteases. When these particles encounter a tumor::: the peptides are cleaved and excreted in the urine::: where they can be easily detected. In animal models of lung cancer::: these biomarkers can detect the presence of tumors early on; however::: they don't reveal the exact location of the tumor or whether the tumor has spread beyond its organ of origin. Building on their previous efforts::: the MIT researchers wanted to develop what they call a ‚Äúmultimodal‚Äù diagnostic::: which can perform both molecular screening (detecting the urinary signal) and imaging::: to tell them exactly where the original tumor and any metastases are located. To modify the particles so they could also be used for PET imaging::: the researchers added a radioactive tracer called copper-64. They also coated them with a peptide that is attracted to acidic environments::: such as the microenvironmen
t in tumors::: to induce the particles to accumulate at tumor sites. Once they reach a tumor::: these peptides insert themselves into cell membranes::: creating a strong imaging signal above background noise. The researchers tested the diagnostic particles in two mouse models of metastatic colon cancer::: in which tumor cells travel to and grow in the liver or the lungs. After treatment with a chemotherapy drug commonly used to treat colon cancer::: the researchers were able to use both the urine signal and the imaging agent to track how the tumors responded to treatment. The researchers also found that delivering copper-64 with their nanoparticles offers an advantage over the strategy that is typically used for PET imaging. The PET tracer::: known as FDG::: is a radioactive form of glucose that is taken up by metabolically active cells::: including cancer cells. However::: the heart generates a bright PET signal when exposed to FDG::: and that signal can obscure weaker signals from nearby lung tumors.

column3:
Most of these recommended solutions are fine (assuming narrow interpretation)
.
I do have concerns with the ones that suggest trading liability immunity for compliance with "content moderation regulations" and "share data with researchers" orders. Government (at least in the US) has viewpoint neutrality obligations -\-\ it cannot compel moderation against or audits for any online expression that is not illegal offline::: which already excludes the vast majority of what the hoi polloi consider disinformation or hate speech or discriminatory expression. Any regulation against amplification must be likewise subject to government viewpoint neutrality obligations.
Also::: interoperabilit
y standards cannot compel invasive product integration; at most::: it can compel data export::: which the big platforms already facilitate.

"Despite tremendous progress in being able to perform calculations with low error rates with superconducting
quantum bits (qubits)::: errors persist in two-qubit gates::: one of the building blocks of quantum computing:::" said Youngkyu Sung::: a graduate student at MIT. Electrical engineering and computer science::: who is lead author of a paper published today in Physical Review X on the subject. "We've demonstrated a way to sharply reduce these errors." In quantum computers::: information processing is an extremely delicate process performed by fragile qubits::: which are highly susceptible to dissonance::: i.e. loss of their quantum mechanical behavior. Previous research led by Sung and his collaborator research group MIT Engineering Quantum Systems proposed tunable couplers that allow researchers to switch two-qubit interactions on and off to control their operation while protecting fragile qubits. The idea of the tunable connector represented a significant advance and was cited::: for example::: by Google as the key to the final demonstration of the advantage quantum computing has over classical computing. Yet addressing error mechanisms is like peeling an onion: peeling one layer reveals the next. In this case::: even when using tunable combiners::: the two-qubit gates were still prone to errors caused by the now undesired interactions between the two qubits and the combiner with the two qubits. Such undesirable interactions were often overlooked before adjustable couplers as they were unobtrusive - but now they do. And since such residual errors increase with the number of qubits and gates::: they stand in the way of creating larger-scale quantum processors. The Physical Review X paper provides a new approach to reducing type errors. William D. Oliver::: associate professor of electrical engineering::: said::: ‚ÄúWe've taken the tunable coupler concept further and 99 percent for the two main types of two-qubit gates::: known as Controlled-Z gates and iSWAP gates. We showed accuracy close to 9:::‚Äù he says. and computer science::: member of the MIT Lincoln Lab::: director of the Center for Quantum Engineering::: and deputy director of the Electronics Research Lab::: home of the Engineering Quantum Systems group. "Higher accuracy gates increase the number of operations that can be performed::: and more operations mean the implementation of more complex algorithms at larger scales." To eliminate error-causing qubit-qubit interactions::: the researchers used higher energy levels of the linker to cancel problematic interactions. "Better control and design of the combiner is key to tailoring the qubit-qubit interaction as we want. This can be accomplished by engineering the existing multi-level dynamics." "Qubit errors can be dealt with effectively by adding redundancy:::" Oliver says::: but such a process can only be performed if the gates are good enough::: with certain error-correctio
n protocol-depend
ent qubits::: Oliver says. "Today::: the softest thresholds are around 99 percent. But in practice::: crossover fidelities are required much higher than this threshold to live with a reasonable level of hardware redundancy." devices used in the research "Manufacturing high-consistenc
y devices is one step towards implementing high-accuracy control:::" says Sung. "The high error rates in two-qubit gates allow quantum hardware to solve problems of quantum chemistry simulation and optimization:::" says Sung. "Up until this point::: only small molecules have been simulated on quantum computers::: simulations could easily be performed on classical computers." In this sense::: our new approach to reducing two-qubit gate errors is our new approach in quantum computing. just in time and helps address one of today's most critical quantum hardware problems:::" he says.

ave Observatory (LIGO) in the United States and Virgo in Italy. The events are named GW200105 and GW200115 for the date each gravitational wave was observed. Both signals represent the final moments as a black hole and a neutron star spiraling together. For GW200105::: the black hole is estimated to be about 9 times the mass of the sun::: with a companion neutron star of about 1.9 solar masses. It is estimated that the two objects merged about 900 million years ago. GW200115 is the product of a 6 solar-mass black hole that collided with a neutron star about 1.5 times the mass of our sun about 1 billion years ago. In both cases

The complexity of milk Nyquist and her team sourced breast milk from more than a dozen donors for her thesis. These samples are given immediately after birth::: about 40 weeks later::: which gives an idea of how breast milk changes over time. ‚ÄúWe recorded many environmental factors that changed::: such as whether the child started kindergarten::: whether the mother started menstruating::: or whether the mother started hormonal birth control:::‚Äù Nyquist says. "Any of these common factors could explain the compositional changes we're witnessing." Nyquist also suggested that discoveries about breast milk could be a surrogate for studying breast tissue. Because breast tissue is necessary for breastfeeding::: researchers have historically struggled to collect tissue samples. ‚ÄúDespite producing an important source of early nutrition::: not much is known about the cellular composition of human breast tissue during lactation:::‚Äù he adds. Overall::: the team found a lot of heterogeneity among donors::: suggesting that breast milk is more complex than expected. They witnessed that the cells in the milk were primarily composed of a type of structural cell that increased in number over time. His team suggested that this transformation may be due to the high turnover of mammary epithelial tissue during breastfeeding. While the reasons are still unclear::: their data adds to previous understandings of the field. Other aspects of their findings confirmed some early discoveries about important immune cells in breast milk.

Nyquist is now a PhD candidate studying computational and systems biology. Their work is co-recommended by professors Alex Shalek and Bonnie Berger and uses machine learning to understand single-cell genomic data. Since this technology can be applied to almost any living material::: the focus was left to choose Nyquist. After flipping through potential thesis ideas::: Nyquist finally decided to work on lactation::: an important and overlooked topic in human development. She and postdoctoral Brittany Goods are now part of the MIT Dairy Study::: the first longitudinal study to profile cells in human breast milk using single-cell genomic data. "Many people don't realize that there are actually living cells in breast milk. Our research is to see what the different cell types are and what they can do:::" says Nyquist. Outside of her own research::: Nyquist enjoys mentoring and teaching other scientists. One of her favorite experiences was teaching coding at HSSP::: a multi-week program for middle and high school students run by MIT students. This experience prompted him to think of ways to make coding accessible to students of any background. ‚ÄúIt can be difficult to tell whether it's easy or hard to tell::: because both can scare people away. ‚ÄúI try to get people excited enough that they can learn the basics and build the confidence to dive deeper:::‚Äù he says. After graduation::: Nyquist hopes to continue her love of mentoring by pursuing a career as a professor. She plans to deepen her research on uterine health by examining how different potentially infectious diseases affect female reproductive tissues. Its purpose is to provide more information about biological processes that have long been considered taboo. "It's crazy to me that we have so much more to learn about important issues like periods::: breastfeeding or menopause:::" Nyquist says. "For example::: we don't understand how certain medications affect people differently during pregnancy. Some doctors tell pregnant women to stop taking their antidepressants
because they worry it will affect their baby. In reality::: there's actually a lot we don't know." ‚ÄúWhen I tell people this is my career direction::: they often say it's hard to get funding for women's reproductive health research because it only affects 50 percent of the population:::‚Äù she says. Nuclei is a medium called Anhydric Monolithic Sensation Yield::: aka N.A.M.S.Y.

A new technique for correcting disease-causing
mutations
The new method::: developed by McGovern Institute researchers::: could lead to safer::: more efficient gene therapies.

Gene editing::: or deliberately altering a gene's DNA sequence::: is a powerful tool to study how mutations cause disease and to modify an individual's DNA for therapeutic purposes. A new method of gene editing that can be used for both purposes has been developed by a team led by Guoping Feng::: James W. (1963) and the Patricia T. Poitras Professor of Brain and Cognitive Sciences at MIT.

‚ÄúThis technical advance can accelerate the production of disease models in animals and opens up a whole new methodology for correcting critically disease-causing
mutations:::‚Äù says Feng::: a fellow at the Broad Institute of Harvard and MIT. Deputy director of the McGovern Institute for Brain Research at MIT. The new findings were published May 26 in the journal Cell.

Genetic disease models

The main goal of the Feng lab is to define exactly what goes wrong with neurodevelopmen
tal and neuropsychiatri
c disorders by designing animal models that carry the gene mutations that cause these disorders in humans. Together with gene editing tools::: new models can be created by injecting a piece of DNA carrying the desired mutation into embryos.

In one such method::: the gene editing tool CRISPR is programmed to cut a targeted gene::: thereby activating natural DNA mechanisms that "repair" the broken gene with the injected template DNA. The engineered cells are then used to create offspring that can pass on the genetic change to subsequent generations::: creating a stable genetic line in which diseases and treatments are tested.

While CRISPR has sped up the process of creating such disease models::: the process could take months or years. The reasons for the inefficiency are that many treated cells never undergo the desired DNA sequence change::: and the change only occurs in one of the two gene copies (for most genes::: each cell contains two versions::: one from the father and the other from the father). mother).

To improve the efficiency of the gene editing process::: the Feng lab team initially assumed that adding a DNA repair protein called RAD51 to a standard mix of CRISPR gene editing tools would increase the chances of a cell (in this case::: a fertilized mouse). egg or single-cell embryo) will undergo the desired genetic change.

As a test case::: they measured the rate of being able to insert ("knock-in") an autism-related mutation in the Chd2 gene. The overall proportion of correctly arranged embryos remained unchanged::: but surprisingly::: both chromosomes carried a significantly higher percentage of desired gene regulation. Tests with a different gene gave the same unexpected result.

‚ÄúIt is normally very rare for both chromosomes to be rearranged at the same time:::‚Äù explains postdoctoral Jonathan Wilde. "The high rate of editing seen with RAD51 was truly striking::: and what began as a simple attempt to make mutant Chd2 mice quickly evolved into a much larger project focused on applications of RAD51 and genome editing:::" says co-author Wilde. Cell newspaper with research scientist Tomomi Aida.

molecular copying machine

The Feng lab team then set out to understand the mechanism by which RAD51 improves gene regulation. They hypothesized that RAD51 is engaged in a process called interhomologous
repair (IHR)::: whereby a DNA break in one chromosome is repaired using the second copy of the chromosome (from the other parent) as a template.

To test this::: they injected mouse embryos with RAD51 and CRISPR::: but left out the template DNA. They programmed CRISPR to cut only the gene sequence on one of the chromosomes::: and then tested whether it was repaired to match the sequence on the uncut chromosome. For this experiment::: they had to use mice with different sequences on their maternal and paternal chromosomes.

They found that control embryos injected with CRISPR alone rarely showed IHR repair. However::: the addition of RAD51 significantly increased the number of embryos in which the CRISPR-targeted
gene was edited to match the uncut chromosome.

‚ÄúPrevious studies of UST have found it to be incredibly inefficient in most cells:::‚Äù Wilde says. Our finding that it occurs much more easily in embryonic cells and can be enhanced by RAD51 suggests that a deeper understanding of what allows this type of DNA repair in the embryo could help us design safer and more efficient gene therapies.

A new way to fix disease-causing
mutations

Standard gene therapy strategies that rely on injecting a corrective piece of DNA to act as a template to repair the mutation engage a process called homology-direct
ed repair (HDR).

Then the two points will be ‚Äúdropped‚Äù at the exact same orbit when the circle point finishes one circle orbit changes.

MIT Syncopasian
May 16 at 12:36 PM ¬∑

For a long time::: Syncopasian has wanted to perform a piece that celebrates the strength and diversity of the Asian American community. I discovered what the electron is.

At what velocity does an electron emits a photon?
Feynman's wrong answer to the question:
‚ÄúAn electron emits an ordinary photon in response to being struck by a reverse-time ("advanced") photon that has traveled backward in time from some point in the future.‚ÄùSome point in the future" could range from femtoseconds (or less) away up to billions of years in the future. me photon travels along the classical time path as a normal or "retarded" photon (no I did not make that up)::: and eventually strikes the very same target that emitted the advanced photon sometime in the future.‚Äù

What did you learn about the electric field?

The electric field or the E-field is a physical field that surrounds every electric charge and exerts force on all other charges in the field::: either attracting or repelling them.

The electric field acts between two charges like the gravitational field acts between two masses::: as they both obey an inverse-square law with distance.

The Coulomb law states that::: for stationary charges::: the electric field varies with the source charge and varies inversely with the square of the distance from the source.

The study of electric fields created by stationary charges is named electrostatics.
Electrostatic fields are electric fields which do not change with time::: which happens when charges and currents are stationary and in that case the Coulomb law fully describes the field.
The electric field can be visualized with a set of lines::: a concept introduced by Michael Faraday. The field's strength is proportional to the density of the lines.
The field lines are the paths that a point positive charge would follow as it is forced to move within the field::: similar to trajectories that masses follow within a gravitational field.

The electric field is defined mathematically as a vector field.

The Coulomb force on a charge of magnitude q at any point in space is equal to F=qE::: the product of the charge and the electric field at that point.

Because of the linearity of Maxwell's equations::: electric fields satisfy the superposition principle:
E(x) = E1(x)+E2(x)

This means the total electric field::: at x::: is equal to the vector sum of the electric fields at that point due to the individual charges.
The total field is then found by integrating over the volume of the charge distribution.

Œ¶ the electric potential::: E = -ÔÉë Œ¶ is analogous to the gravitational potential. Mass is sometimes called ‚Äògravitational charge‚Äô.

This implies similarities between the electric field E and the gravitational field g or their associated potentials.

A proton is a subatomic particle::: symbol p with a positive electric charge of +1e elementary charge.
The neutron is a subatomic particle::: symbol n::: which has a neutral (not positive or negative) charge. The neutron is not affected by electric fields.
The protons within the nucleus are repelled by the long-range electromagnetic
force::: but short-range::: nuclear force binds the nucleons closely together.
A free neutron is unstable::: decaying to a proton::: electron and antineutrino with a mean lifetime close to 15 minutes.

The positron is the antiparticle of the electron. The positron has an electric charge of +1 e. When a positron collides with an electron::: annihilation occurs. If this collision occurs at low energies::: it results in the production of two photons.

All physicists::: all scientists::: all Nobel Laureates::: your professors‚Ä¶can not explain this thing: rub a comb through your hair and use it to lift pieces of paper.

The electrons do repel each other.
An electron has the opposite charge properties to a positive charge.

So an electron will move away from another negative charge::: and towards a positive charge. The force experienced by a charge is F=E‚ãÖq

Mr. Joe Biden

Subject: An opener letter to the President of United State of America
VIRTUAL GLOBAL CLIMATE SUMMIT on April 22-23: 2021.
Your Excellency:::
In recent years::: scientists have underscored the need to limit planetary warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius in order to stave off the worst impacts of climate change. A key goal of the Global Climate Summit is expected to crystalize efforts that will keep 1.5- degree goal within reach. The Summit will also highlight examples of how the enhanced climate change will help ensure a safer future for the humanity through advance innovative technologies::: and help vulnerable countries to counter the much dreaded climate impacts.
Sind Tas Water Council Pakistan is a Think Forum::: working for the future generations to not simply survive::: but to thrive. We want to build a world where the balance between people and the environment::: value and profit::: people‚Äôs beliefs and
actions would be maintained and where human::: natural and capital resources would become a force for good. For that::: we must change and heal the nature of our relationships::: ensuring we respect each other and the very elements that allow us to live.
It is heartening that the ‚ÄúVIRTUAL GLOBAL CLIMATE SUMMIT‚Äù is been convened by you. 40 countries most likely to be impacted by the climate would be participating in the summit. Pakistan has been overlooked Mr. President Pakistan is a big victim of the climate change however we are taking measures to fight against the change. Our main concerns are:-
(i) World‚Äôs biggest glaciers in the mountains are receding at an alarming rate. These glaciers are the primary source of fresh water for hundreds of million people.
(ii) Three rivers i.e.::: Sutlej::: Bias and Ravi were given by Pakistan to India in 1960 for unrestricted use. The valleys of these rivers are already heavy stress because of the climate change.
(iii) This is a humanitarian disaster. A very large treat of forests has already been destroyed.(iv) Pakistan‚Äôs heavy dependence on agriculture and serious water shortages
coupled with a fast growing population is a disaster in waiting. Pakistan is susceptibility to floods and drought underscore its fragility. We ranked as one of the world‚Äôs 10 most climate-vulnera
ble nations.
(v) With a population of 220 million::: the world‚Äôs fifth largest::: there are immense human dimensions to this vulnerability.
The Government of Pakistan has aggressively move to counter these. For example:-
(a) Pakistan::: after a long span of 45 years has started constructing two major dams.
(b) It is well in its way to plant billions of trees.
(c) Pakistan is reducing the use of plastics and is switching to use biodegradable materials.
We strongly propose that this sensitive human issue be reconsidered by keeping aside all political or other interests and Pakistan may also be invited in the summit. All other top-10 population countries received invitations to
Virtual Summit. Some Pakistanis depict it as a deliberate snub.
We look forward to a more human and positive response from you for the sake of humanity and the future of our tiny blue planet.
With Best Regards
Muhammad Suleman Khan
Chairman

The goal of this video is not to simply recount history::: but to understand how we can stop the devil from ever ruling the world again. This relies on each individual‚Äôs enlightenment::: proactive abandonment of evil::: and return to the traditions and way of life that the divine laid down for man.

The divine will triumph over the devil. Which side we stand on will determine our eternal destiny.

Following the Cold War::: the poison of communism not only continued to harm formerly communist countries::: but also spread throughout the world. Since then::: the ideological infiltration of communism has enabled the specter to influence human society on a global scale::: and now many people even think that the dark wishes of communism are their own. Communism: A Devil Bent on the Destruction of Humanity

Socialism: The Preliminary Stage of Communism

In the West::: many view socialism and communism as being separate::: which provides fertile ground for socialism to flourish. In fact::: according to Marxist-Leninis
t theory::: socialism is simply communism‚Äôs preliminary stage.

In 1875::: in Critique of the Gotha Programme::: Marx put forward the idea that there is an initial phase of communism::: which is followed by a ‚Äúhigher‚Äù phase. Friedrich Engels::: compelled by changes in the international situation in his later years::: also proposed ‚Äúdemocratic socialism:::‚Äù in which votes were used to obtain political power. Democratic socialism was adopted by social democratic party leaders and theorists of the Second International and led to the left-wing parties in many capitalist countries around the world today. Later::: Lenin set down clear definitions of socialism and communism: He considered socialism to be the preliminary phase of communism::: and communism to be developed on the basis of socialism. The state ownership and planned economy of socialism are part of the initial preparation for communism.

Socialism has always been part of Marxism and the international communist movement. While branches of socialism or left-wing doctrines popular in the West seem superficially unrelated to communism::: they are nonviolent forms of the same root ideology. Left-wing parties come to power in Western countries through elections::: rather than violent revolution. High taxation serves the same role as the outright state ownership seen under communist regimes::: and excessive social welfare is used in place of planned economics. Creating a welfare state is an important aspect of realizing socialism in Western countries.

Outside of research and design::: my main passion is making music::: writes Alexis Hope::: research assistant in the MIT Media Lab. Just over a decade ago::: I started a band with my friends Matthew Longoria and Kabir Vermouth called Calico Beach Party::: and we‚Äôve been playing together ever since::: even though we live on opposite sides of the country.

The song in this video::: ‚ÄúYou Got Me Bad:::‚Äù is one of the first songs we ever wrote together::: and playing it helps me imagine the sweet times ahead when we can all gather again safely. I love that music connects us to other people even when we are far apart. A song is a conversation with others::: a chance to see inside someone‚Äôs brain::: and an opportunity to learn something new.

Learn more about her work at the Media Lab and her passions: media.mit.edu/videos/ml-voices-alexis-hope/

Wave‚Äìparticle duality is the concept in quantum mechanics that every particle can be described as either a particle or a wave::: depending upon the circumstances of the experiment.

Wave-particle duality is the possession by light and electrons of both wavelike and particle-like characteristics
.

Wave-particle duality refers to the fundamental property of matter where at one moment it appears like a wave and at another moment it acts like a particle.

The description of light as waves was well-known::: but the photoelectric effect introduced firm evidence of a particle nature as well.
The particle properties of electrons were well known when the DeBroglie hypothesis and the subsequent experiments by Davisson and Germer established the wave nature of the electron.

Albert Einstein wrote:
‚ÄòWe are faced with a new kind of difficulty. We have two contradictory pictures of reality; separately neither of them fully explains the phenomena of light::: but together they do.‚Äô

De Broglie had proposed a pilot wave construct to explain the observed wave-particle duality. Each particle has a well-defined position and momentum::: but is guided by a wave function derived from Schr√∂dinger's equation.

Double-slit experiment
In 1807 Thomas Young asserted that light has the properties of a wave in an experiment called Young‚Äôs Interference Experiment::: showed that lights (waves) passing through two slits (double-slit) add together or cancel each other and then interference fringes appear. This phenomenon cannot be explained unless light is considered as a wave.

The double-slit experiment with electrons. The pictures show the pattern you get on the second wall as more and more electrons are fired. The result is a stripy interference pattern. The spots where electrons hit::: build up to replicate the interference pattern from a wave.
Particles such as electrons combine characteristics
of particles and characteristics
of waves. That's the famous wave particle duality of quantum mechanics.

The photoelectric effect is a phenomenon where photons (light quanta) have the properties not only of a wave but also of a particle.

To explain what the wave-particle duality means is a key point of debate in quantum physics.
There are many interpretations
but they are all bound by the same set of wave equations and must explain the same experimental observations.
This ability to describe reality in the form of a wave function::: generally in the form of the Schrodinger equation is at the heart of quantum mechanics.

There is no consensus on the genuine meaning of wave-particle duality and the interpretation of quantum theory.
The wave-particle duality is a fundamental property of the nature. At the same time::: it is one of the greatest mysteries of modern physics.

Sometimes electrons behave as particles in beta radiation and sometimes as waves in electron diffraction::: in the double-slit experiment.

It was an assurance designed to bolster public confidence in the way America votes: Voting machines ‚Äúare not connected to the internet.‚Äù
Then Acting Undersecretary for Cybersecurity and Communications at the Department of Homeland Security Jeanette Manfra said those words in 2017::: testifying before Congress while she was responsible for the security of the nation‚Äôs voting system.
So many government officials like Manfra have said the same thing over the last few years that it is commonly accepted as gospel by most Americans. Behind it is the notion that if voting systems are not online::: hackers will have a harder time compromising them.
But that is an overstatement::: according to a team of 10 independent cybersecurity experts who specialize in voting systems and elections. While the voting machines themselves are not designed to be online::: the larger voting systems in many states end up there::: putting the voting process at risk.
That team of election security experts say that last summer::: they discovered some systems are::: in fact::: online.
‚ÄúWe found over 35 [voting systems] had been left online and we‚Äôre still continuing to find more:::‚Äù Kevin Skoglund::: a senior technical advisor at the election security advocacy group National Election Defense Coalition::: told NBC News. NBC NEWS
Jan. 10::: 2020::: 3:36 PM PST
By Kevin Monahan::: Cynthia McFadden and Didi Martinez

column3:
Here silly me I made some childish mistakes... or not? We should examine it.

What is dark matter and dark energy?

Dark energy and dark matter are probabilistic phenomena of similar nature.
In relatively near regions dark energy and dark matter aren't locally detectable
.
Dark energy is ambiguity of the wave function when observed from afar::: it has to generate alternative microstates (the macrostate is a bigger local area::: and/or the universe):::

and dark matter is loss of microstates which cannot survive in some local macrostate (they cancel out).

It is like a mathematical mapping function (in mathematics) in witch if we have set X and set Y:::
two elements of the set X might correspond to a single element of the set Y (that phenomenon is dark matter)::: and other extra elements without correspondence (non-entangled)
can exist in set Y (that phenomenon is dark energy).

https://
en.wikipedia.org
/wiki/
Map_(mathematics
)

Is unitarity maintained in that overall process? No and yes. Unitarity is theoretically always kept::: but in a renormalization
manner of infinite matryoshka dolls. No human observer has access to the infinitely bigger matryoshka doll (which probabilistic contributes negligibly)::: and that huge hypergrouping exists way beyond our local Hubble volume.

Is Lagrangian mechanics correct? That question makes no sense and no it's not correct. It makes no sense because each coordinate point used in the function is interpreted to be in an area. We can reshape this formulas though in a manner which include probability.

Completely ecological industrial platform without any gas emittion or other polluting materials. 2. Burning thousands of tonnes of household waste annually per furnace (without needing selection). 3. Alternative fuel production at competitive prices and in massive amounts. 4. Waste processing and industrial pollution neutralising of any kind (even burning gasses) 5. Redoxint project introduces a series of novelties at conception::: which requires design and simulation::: in order to have a comprehensive view on technology Pollution appears when the technological progress reaches a level where it starts having a major impact upon the environment and the by-products management is not prioritised because of economic reasons. Massive gas emission with greenhouse effect are the result of a faulty attitude towards technology. In the same category one should include household and industrial waste management.  The level of pollution is so high that a change in attitude is needed towards the environment.  The Redoxint procedure is complex without being complicated::: combines existing technologies with innovation and it is in one word: The Future.  One of the most dangerous products for the environment are carbides. The release of carbon monoxide in the air is a big financial and energy related issue. The first patent that the Redoxing project is based upon describes a procedure and a processing equipment that processes carbides in a Tunnel Furnace.  The Tunnel Furnace used as an electrochemical reactor provides result gases at reasonable temperatures for them to be used as primary raw material for synthesis processing equipments (Fischer-Tropsc h::: Urea).  All these equipment can process huge amounts of gases that were released in the special temperature conditions specific to the Tunnel Furnace.  Carbide production happens at very high temperatures and the energy produced by the electrochemical reaction can be used for burning the household waste. The released gases of this burning procedure (at more than 1000¬∞C) will enter the synthesis processing equipment::: without any gas being released in the atmosphere.  The massive carbide production is justified by the use in the dehydration of ethyl alcohol obtained from the fermentation technology and cellulose producing technology. Both of them have alcohol in water as outcome.  The second patent included in the Redoxint project deals with the utilisation of the carbide obtained in eco-friendly conditions for the dehydration of ethyl alcohol. The dehydrated ethyl alcohol is the alternative energy source of the future when the cost is regulated by the Redoxint procedure. Also the massive quantities of acetylene obtained is an exceptional raw material in the synthesis chemical industry. Acetylene is the raw material used in the chemical industry that leads to the production of all the organic products::: from rubber to plastic materials and drugs::: dyes::: alternative fuel or synthetic fibres. I do not want to insist any further on the major importance of the acetylene::: the main point is that acetylene is the most important raw material for the organic and synthesis chemical industry.  At the end of the Redoxint production cycle::: there are two main products: Ca(OH)2 (slaked lime) and the ash produced by the waste burning::: both of them used as construction materials.  The Redoxint project is a perfectly eco-friendly industrial platform which gives the opportunity for other processing equipments to be attached to the existing platforms for processing by-products and for utilising the renewable energy of the Redoxint platform. There can be attached biodiesel processing equipments (which use alcohol)::: food industry and construction material equipments. The Tunnel Furnace can even process chemical industry gas by-products.  This kind of industrial platforms can be built anywhere in the world::: no exception. The platform‚Äôs dependency is only on the amount of green-house gases that need to be processed and house hold waste that needs to be burned. By combining more production centres::: the production can reach millions of tons of house-hold waste and just as much greenhouse gases that need to be processed each year.  In the case that the Redoxint technology has to be extended::: it is flexible enough to permit it. The amounts of dehydrated alcohol::: biodiesel and synthetic fuel from the Fischer-Tropsch equipment are comparable at price with the conventional energy sources. Also in the case of several platforms combined::: there is always the possibility of completely replacing the conventional energy sources.  The Redoxint technology is exceptional through simplicity and through the combination of already in use technologies with innovative one on one industrial platform. The capacity of becoming highly modular and the adaptability of Redoxint is sufficient to allow the reshape of the existing technological industry platforms.  Processing flue gases from the furnace tunnel in Solvay plant for seawater desalination offers the cheapest drinking water EXPENSES production are minimal::: considering that all reagents are byproducts of peripheral tunnel furnace installations Such production's expense are transferred acetylene's expense with the raw materials and energy for desalination are theoretically zero Redoxint process used for seawater desalination has the lowest production cost and quantity of drinking water most between the previous process Redoxint process offers solutions for two fundamental requirements in desalination::: low price::: and the maximum quantities of desalinated water If there is already functional Solvay plant::: construction furnace and peripheral installations are very easy to make  In the case of chemical industry::: one can imagine and adapt massive equipments for sea water desalinisation::: massive construction material production (like concrete)::: and all the platforms that can be described as eco-friendly and with a good waste management. column6: It appears that if we ourselves become extinct or otherwise fail to colonize space::: it‚Äôs game over for life itself.  I‚Äôll explain:  As far as we can tell::: life eventually will become extinct on this planet whether we are here to witness it or not.  It is astronomically rare for a species of life to develop the capacity to entertain that apparently simple thought. In the entire history of life on Earth::: only one species of life appears ever to have evolved with the capacity to be aware of what to us appears to be a simple fact of geo-biological reality.  That species is us. We are unique.  Life is generally unaware of its fate. Should the human species become extinct::: should we choose::: for example::: to flush our rare gift of choice down the toilet of a self-induced climate oblivion::: and considering historical past performance::: it seems highly unlikely that life‚Äôs capacity to notice its otherwise unsupervised destiny will re-evolve before the clock runs out on life‚Äôs collective reproductive project.  If we ourselves become extinct or otherwise fail to colonize space::: then life itself as a single::: complex organism confined to this planet will fail to reproduce by pinching itself in half::: by forming two clones::: two curiously-named ‚Äúdaughter cells‚Äù which then wander off to have adventures of their own in time and space independently of each other::: until::: in the fullness of time::: they repeat the process::: and so on::: and so forth.  If life on Earth now declines to negotiate its collective mortality with reproduction::: it will expire in a single and apparently unique generation.  Like it or not::: we appear to have superpowers. Superman‚Äôs cape fits.  The destiny of life itself is in our hands. It‚Äôs our choice. How do we wish to proceed?

column11: Remark  Ïõ®Ïñ¥Îü¨Î∏î ÏõåÏπòÏóê Ï†ÅÏö© Í∞ÄÎä•ÏÑ±ÏùÑ ÌÉÄÏßÑÌï† MIT Í≥µÍ≥ºÎåÄÌïô ÏïÑÏù¥ÌÖú  Bio Optics World  Optical sensor-driven device can count white blood cells through the skin A portable optical device for placing on the fingertip can count white blood cells without a blood test. BioOptics World Editors Oct 1st::: 2015  An international team of researchers has developed a portable device for placing on the fingertip that counts white blood cells without a blood test. The technology‚Äîwhic h combines an optical sensor with algorithms‚Äîis designed for use on chemotherapy patients::: who could know their immune system levels in real time. It could also have utility in detecting serious infections.  The project::: known as Leuko::: has been financed by Madrid-MIT M+Visi√≥n::: a consortium that seeks to foster collaboration between research centers and hospitals in the region of Madrid with the Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT; Cambridge::: MA) and other centers in the Boston area. The Center of Future Technologies in Cancer Care and the Coulter Foundation are also supporting the project::: and the total amount raised has been close to $450:::000 (400:::000 euros).  Carlos Castro::: an engineer specializing in biomedicine who is working in the Research Laboratory of Electronics at MIT::: says that the new device will allow white blood cells to be measured simply and painlessly. "Patients undergoing chemotherapy will be able to use a 'leukometer' in the future to estimate the state of their immune system:::" he adds::: pointing out that the technology opens up the possibility to personalize chemotherapy treatment according to the immunological response for each patient. In the case of patients with lymphomas and leukemia::: treatment doses could be maximized for each individual without compromising their immunological system. Treatment efficiency could be improved while reducing the risk of suffering serious infections::: he says.  Researchers are working to miniaturize the device for white blood cell counting which could be used in a similar way to the pulse oximeter shown in the image::: used to measure oxygen levels in the blood. (Credit: Quinn Dombrowski) The technology includes a portable optical system::: which provides oblique illumination with LEDs and is able to capture images of superficial capillaries under the skin with cellular resolution. The acquired videos are subsequently analyzed by automatic algorithms capable of detecting white blood cells and calculating their concentration. These algorithms::: which have been protected by a patent filing::: were presented at the Annual International Conference of the IEEE Engineering in Medicine and Biology Society::: held August 25-29::: 2015::: in Milan::: Italy.  Castro explains that the device is placed on the patient's fingertip in a similar way to how pulse oximeters are used in hospitals to measure blood oxygen levels. With a small lens::: the system captures images of capillaries very close to the surface in the nailbed. When illuminating at certain frequencies::: light is absorbed by the hemoglobin in the red cells::: an effect that does not happen with the white cells. This means that the leukocytes appear as small transparent particles moving inside the capillary. Subsequently::: the project's image processing algorithms recognize these events and count them::: providing an estimate for their concentration in the blood::: he adds.  The portable device will allow patients to carry out these measurements at home in the future::: so it will no longer be necessary for them to travel to a hospital or clinic. Castro says that other medical areas where the device could have use is preventing sepsis and early diagnosis of a bacterial or viral infection.  One prototype is a portable microscope which is placed manually on the patient‚Äôs fingertip to take videos of microcirculatio n in very superficial capillaries. (Credit: Research Laboratory of Electronics/ MIT) There are currently three different prototypes. One of them is a portable microscope that is placed manually on the patient's finger to take videos of their microcirculatio n in very superficial capillaries. This device has already been tested on 31 patients in Hospital Fuenlabrada in Madrid and on six more in Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston. "We are now working to improve its accuracy and reliability:::" Castro says.  A second version of the prototype includes modifications to the microscope to improve the stability and quality of the images. The third one is a small optical piece that can be added to a mobile phone camera to obtain images of the circulation in the capillaries. "These images could then be transmitted to a server where the algorithms would analyze them and give an estimate from the analysis:::" according to Castro.  Castro thinks that by the beginning of 2017::: an initial beta product could be available for people willing to try it through crowdfunding platforms such as Indiegogo. With sufficient funding::: the research team could develop a final product that meets European regulations by the beginning of 2019. column22: From the President of Harvard University...  Dear Members of the Harvard Community:::  I am delighted to report that today the United States government withdrew the US Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) directive that::: among other things::: would have prevented international students from staying in the country if they attend institutions that are holding their courses online this fall. This withdrawal has nationwide effect.  This is a significant victory. The directive had disrupted all of American higher education. I have heard from countless international students who said that the July 6 directive had put them at serious risk. These student‚Äîour students‚Äîcan now rest easier and focus on their education::: which is all they ever wanted to do. While the government may attempt to issue a new directive::: our legal arguments remain strong and the Court has retained jurisdiction::: which would allow us to seek judicial relief immediately to protect our international students should the government again act unlawfully. This means we expect that the 2020‚Äì2021 academic year will proceed as we have carefully planned::: in our effort both to protect the health and safety of our students and others and to ensure that learning can go on in the best possible way under the current unprecedented circumstances.  We are immensely grateful for the widespread support that we and our students have received over the course of the past week. Hundreds of colleges and universities::: cities::: labor unions::: companies::: civic organizations::: and higher education associations filed amicus briefs in support of the complaint that we filed jointly with MIT. We also received support from Massachusetts Attorney General Maura Healey::: who joined 17 attorneys general from across the United States in filing a similar complaint.  This show of support is heartening. We all recognize the value that international students bring to our campuses::: to this nation::: and to the world. We recognize::: too::: that colleges and universities must pursue their educational missions while carefully protecting the health and safety of their students::: faculty::: and staff. At a time when this pandemic continues to rage::: we must continue to act with vigilance::: informed by the best available science and with a commitment both to carrying forward the vital enterprise of learning and to safeguarding public health. The ICE directive sought to force each of us to choose between the health of our communities and the education of our international students‚Äîa false and dangerous choice which we rejected. In the end::: the public overwhelmingly agreed with us::: and the government::: in response::: withdrew its order.  Higher education in the United States seeks and attracts the best and the brightest students from around the world. They strengthen our universities immeasurably::: and we aim to provide them with the best education possible‚Äîin a virtuous cycle that benefits all of us. Some will seek to stay in this country::: thanks to the freedoms and opportunities that they find here. And those who return home will do so enriched by the values we hold dear.  I am grateful to my colleagues across the University who have tirelessly fought to achieve today‚Äôs important result. Many worked literally through the night to ensure that justice prevailed. We owe all of them our thanks. I look forward to the day when we can welcome our entire community back to campus. In the meantime::: we remain dedicated to our academic mission::: and to enabling the best possible education for our students while affirming our deep commitment to the health of people in our own community and beyond.  Sincerely::: Larry  _______________ _____ Lawrence S. Bacow President Harvard University

column9: The blood brain barrier has been a suspect target for quite some time. The barrier dilates ONLY when a person reaches REM sleep and then it functions as a means of flushing the brain of amyloid plaques (not mentioned in the article). I would focus on the astrocytic feet which have multiple functions in the maintenance and regulation of the blood brain barrier. And lets not forget the circumventricul ar organs as being a possible vector for viral brain infection because they lack a blood brain barrier due to needing access to the bloodstream... The jury is still out as to weather Alzheimer's is viral in its initial element of causation. Breakdown of the barrier does occur as a consequence of cerebrovascular diseases and traumatic brain injury::: with the former having a genetic causality. GREAT lab work coaxing human induced pluripotent stem cells to become the three types of cells that make up the BBB. And seeing a genetic link to APOE4 - and the 3D rendering of an APOE4-carrying engineered blood vessel shows heavy accumulation of amyloid protein...WOW.. . GREAT work by Joel Blanchard of The Picower Institute for Learning and Memory. We are all checking our 23&me results as we speak ü§®ü§®

Letter to the MIT community regarding the Institute's initial decisions about the fall http://mitsha.re/EWxy50AbhyN  Tl;dr: Our community process did not produce perfect consensus. But we have now settled on the approach that drew the most positive feedback.  To allow students to stay on track to their degrees::: we will maintain the basic two-semester structure of our academic calendar. However::: we may need to start a week early (around Sept. 1)::: end any in-person instruction before Thanksgiving::: and finish the term remotely.  Our undergraduate residential population in the fall will be much less than our normal capacity ‚Äì conceivably as high as 60 percent::: but likely much lower. Exactly how many students can return at any point depends on several factors::: some beyond our control.  With this baseline two-semester decision in place::: we can now begin making the hundreds of subsequent interlocking decisions and arrangements required. We will share our detailed plans for the undergraduate experience no later than the week of July 6th.  Campus life will feel very different this fall.  NEWS.MIT.EDU Letter regarding MIT's initial decisions about the fall
